Topological Deep Learning

Topologies Definition:

Simplical Complexes

Graphes as 1D complex
0-simplex: vertices
1-simplex: edges
→ pairwise relationships
Triangles: 2D complex
0-simplex: vertices
1-simplex: edges
2-simplex: filled triangles
→ 3 way relationships
Tetrahedron: 3D complex (4 points pyramids)
0-simplex: vertices
1-simplex: edges
2-simplex: faces / filled triangles
3-simplex: volume
→ 4 way relationships

Cell Complexes: discrete representations, type-set hierarcht

cell complexes are a generatlization of simplical complexes that follows an interior to boundary hierarchy, and a not limited to complexes structures i.e faces can involve more than three nodes,
0-rank cell: nodes
1-rank cell: edges / bonds
2-rank cell: rings
3-rank cell: cylinder

Combinatorial Complexes: continuous representations interior-boundary structure

(generalization final boss)
A Combinatorial Complex is a triplet (V,X,rk)(\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{X}, \mathcal{rk})(V,X,rk)﻿ where
V\mathcal{V}V﻿ is a set of vertics
X⊂P(V)\mathcal{X} \subset \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{V})X⊂P(V)﻿ a subset of the powerset of V\mathcal{V}V﻿​
rk\mathcal{rk}rk﻿ an order preserving rank function

Topological Lifting

let T1=(F1,X1)\mathcal{T_1} = (\mathcal{F_1}, \mathcal{X_1})T1​=(F1​,X1​)﻿ and T2=(F2,X2)\mathcal{T_2} = (\mathcal{F_2}, \mathcal{X_2})T2​=(F2​,X2​)﻿ two featured topological domains
a lifting from T1\mathcal{T_1}T1​﻿ to T2\mathcal{T_2}T2​﻿ is a pair (ψX,ψF)(\mathcal{\psi}_\mathcal{X}, \mathrm{\psi}_\mathrm{F})(ψX​,ψF​)﻿ where:
Structural lifting:ψX:X1×F1→X2feature lifting: ψF:X1×F1→F2preserving: F2(ψX(x))=ψF(F1(x))\text{Structural lifting:} \quad \quad \quad \quad \quad\mathcal{\psi}_\mathrm{X}: \mathcal{X}_1 \times \mathcal{F}_1 \rightarrow \mathcal{X}_2 \\ \text{feature lifting: \quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad }\mathcal{\psi}_\mathrm{F}: \mathcal{X}_1 \times \mathcal{F}_1 \rightarrow \mathcal{F}_2 \\ \text{preserving: } \quad\quad\quad\quad\quad \mathrm{F}_2(\mathcal{\psi}_\mathrm{X}(x)) = \mathcal{\psi}_\mathrm{F}(\mathrm{F}_1(x))Structural lifting:ψX​:X1​×F1​→X2​feature lifting: ψF​:X1​×F1​→F2​preserving: F2​(ψX​(x))=ψF​(F1​(x))

Topological Neural Nets in k-cochain spaces

k-Cochain spaces:

let Ck(X,Rd)\mathcal{C}^k (\mathcal{X}, \mathbb{R}^d)Ck(X,Rd)﻿ be a R\mathbb{R}R﻿-vector space of functions Hk\mathrm{H}_kHk​﻿ where Hk:Xk→Rd\mathrm{H}_k: \mathcal{X}^k \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^dHk​:Xk→Rd﻿​
elements Hk\mathrm{H}_kHk​﻿ are the k-cochain (k-signals) of the k-cochain space Ck(X,Rd)\mathcal{C}^k (\mathcal{X}, \mathbb{R}^d)Ck(X,Rd)﻿​

TNN: topological neural nets

a topological neural network is function mapping a set of k-signals to another
TNN:Ci1×⋯×Cin→Cj1×⋯×Cjm\mathrm{TNN}: \mathcal{C}^{i_1} \times \dots \times \mathcal{C}^{i_n} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}^{j_1} \times \dots \times \mathcal{C}^{j_m}TNN:Ci1​×⋯×Cin​→Cj1​×⋯×Cjm​

Mathematical Modeling of high-order Complexes

cochains are structured through inter-domain and intra-domain mappings, the adjacency and incidence matrices respectively
formally defined as
for r < k, incidence matrices
Br,k:Ck(X)→Cr(X)Ar,k:Cr(X)→Cr(X)\mathrm{B}_{r, k}: \mathcal{C}^k(\mathcal{X}) \rightarrow \mathcal{C}^r(\mathcal{X})\\ \mathrm{A}_{r, k}: \mathcal{C}^r(\mathcal{X}) \rightarrow \mathcal{C}^r(\mathcal{X})Br,k​:Ck(X)→Cr(X)Ar,k​:Cr(X)→Cr(X)
incidence and adjacency matrices collectively redistribute signals across different dimensional cells

Neighborhood function: N:S→P(P(S))\mathcal{N}: \mathrm{S} \rightarrow \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{P}(\mathrm{S}))N:S→P(P(S))﻿​

HOMP: Higher-Order Message Passing

let X\mathcal{X} X﻿ be a topological domain, let N(x)\mathcal{N}(x)N(x)﻿ denote multi-set { ⁣{N1(x),…,Nn(x)} ⁣}\{\!\{\mathcal{N_1(x)}, \dots, \mathcal{N}_n(x)\}\!\}{{N1​(x),…,Nn​(x)}}﻿ be a set of neighborhood functions defined on X\mathcal{X}X﻿​
given y∈N(x)y \in \mathcal{N}(x)y∈N(x)﻿ and hx(l)h^{(l)}_xhx(l)​﻿ the feature vector of the element xxx﻿ HOMP is defined as:
mx,y=αNx(hx(l),hy(l))mxk=⨁y∈Nk(x)mx,y,1≤k≤nmx=⨂Nk∈N(x)mxkhk(l+1)=β(hx(l),mx)m_{x, y} = \alpha_{\mathcal{N}_x} (h^{(l)}_x, h^{(l)}_y) \\ m^k_x = \bigoplus_{y \in \mathcal{N}_k(x)} m_{x, y}, 1 \le k \le n \\ m_x = \bigotimes_{\mathcal{N}_k \in \mathcal{N}(x)} m^k_x\\ h^{(l+1)}_k = \beta(h^{(l)}_x, m_x)mx,y​=αNx​​(hx(l)​,hy(l)​)mxk​=y∈Nk​(x)⨁​mx,y​,1≤k≤nmx​=Nk​∈N(x)⨂​mxk​hk(l+1)​=β(hx(l)​,mx​)
